            <ArticleTitle>Magneto-optic trap using a reversible, solid-state alkali-metal source.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>3002-3005</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1364/OL.44.003002</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>We demonstrate a novel way to form and deplete a vapor-cell magneto-optic trap (MOT) using a reversible, solid-state alkali-metal source via an applied polarized voltage. Using ∼100  mW of electrical power, a trapped-atom number of 5×10<sup>6</sup> has been achieved, starting from near zero and the timescales of the MOT formation and depletion of ∼1  s. This fast, reversible, and low-power alkali-atom source is desirable in both tabletop and portable cold-atom systems. The core technology of this device should translate readily to other alkali and alkaline-earth elements that could find a wide range of uses in cold-atom systems and instruments.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
